{{Top|canon=Jaig Eyes|title=''Jaig'' eyes}}
{{Otheruses|Eye}}
[[File:RexPhase2close-SWE.png|thumb|250px|[[Clone Captain/Legends|Clone Captain]] [[Rex/Legends|Rex]] wearing his helmet decorated with blue ''jaig'' eyes]]
'''''Jaig'' eyes'''&mdash;a simplification of '''''jai'galaar'la sur'haii'se''''', translating as "[[Shriek-hawk/Legends|shriek-hawk]] [[Eye/Legends|eyes]]" in [[Mando'a/Legends|''Mando'a'']], and more commonly referred to simply as '''''jaig'''''&mdash;were a [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] sigil bestowed by clan leaders as a mark of honor, awarded for particular acts of bravery.

Usually worn upon the [[Armor/Legends|helmet]], the sigil marked Mandalorian [[Soldier/Legends|soldiers]] who had distinguished themselves in battle. When the Mandalorian [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] and [[Mandalore (title)/Legends|''Mand'alor'']] [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]] was chosen as the [[Clone template/Legends|clone template]] for the [[Clone trooper/Legends|clone troopers]] of the [[Grand Army of the Republic/Legends|Grand Army of the Republic]], he and his Mandalorian ''[[Cuy'val Dar]]'' [[Clone commando/Legends|clone]] trainers passed on a number of Mandalorian traditions and customs to Fett's [[Cloning/Legends|clones]], among them the practice of awarding ''jaig'' eyes as an award of courage.

Since the tradition of awarding ''jaig'' eyes to distinguished soldiers began, a number of beings have been awarded the honor, with [[Mandalorian Protectors (Spar)|Mandalorian Protector]] and ''Mand'alor'' [[Fenn Shysa]], [[Clone Captain/Legends|Clone Captain]] [[Rex/Legends|Rex]], [[Special ops clone trooper/Legends|stealth operations clone trooper]] [[Clone Commander/Legends|commander]] [[Blackout/Legends|Blackout]] and [[Advanced Recon Commando/Legends|ARC trooper]] [[Captain/Legends|captain]] [[Fordo]] being among its most notable recipients.

==Description==
''Jaig'' [[Eye/Legends|eyes]] were a [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] sigil, known formally in [[Mando'a/Legends|''Mando'a'']] as ''jai'galaar'la sur'haii'se'', a name which translated as "[[Shriek-hawk/Legends|shriek-hawk]] [[Eye/Legends|eyes]]" in the [[Language/Legends|language]] of [[Galactic Basic Standard/Legends|Galactic Basic Standard]].<ref name="TMPaC">{{InsiderCite|86|The Mandalorians: People and Culture}}</ref> Rendered as a stylized pair of shriek-[[Hawk/Legends|hawk]] eyes,<ref name="GttGAR">{{InsiderCite|84|Guide to the Grand Army of the Republic}}</ref> ''jaig'' were a mark of honor that select Mandalorian clan [[Chief/Legends|chieftains]] bestowed on warriors in recognition of their bravery. They were often painted on the [[Soldier/Legends|soldier's]] [[Armor/Legends|helmet]], or elsewhere on the plates of their [[Mandalorian armor/Legends|armor]].<ref name="TMPaC" />

==History==
[[File:FennShysa.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Fenn Shysa, a Mandalorian recipient of ''jaig'' eyes]]
As its name, ''jai'galaar'la sur'haii'se''—"shriek-hawk eyes"—suggests, ''jaig'' found their origins with the predatory shriek-hawks [[Homeworld/Legends|native]] to the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim]] [[Planet/Legends|world]] of [[Mandalore/Legends|Mandalore]]. Mandalorians had long possessed traditions of marking their armor with personalized sigils: these symbols were often indicative of which clan the Mandalorian belonged to, where their allegiances lay, or identifying loved ones.

The ''jaig'' eyes, however, became a symbol of honor among the Mandalorians, a unique marking awarded by clan chieftains as a means of recognizing a soldier's outstanding bravery.<ref name="TMPaC" /> One such example was [[Fenn Shysa]], a [[Constable/Legends|constable]] and [[Mandalorian Protectors (Spar)|Mandalorian Protector]]<ref name="The History of the Mandalorians">{{InsiderCite|80|The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors}}</ref> so well thought of by his people, he went on to become [[Mandalore (title)/Legends|''Mand'alor'']], traditional leader of all the Mandalorian clans.<ref name="O66">''[[Order 66: A Republic Commando Novel]]''</ref>

This tradition carried over to the millions of [[Clone trooper/Legends|clone soldiers]] of the [[Grand Army of the Republic/Legends|Grand Army of the Republic]],<ref name="GttGAR" /> each a [[Cloning/Legends|clone]] of another ''Mand'alor'', the [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] and [[Mercenary/Legends|mercenary]] [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]].<ref name="O66" /> Fett and the Mandalorian members of the ''[[Cuy'val Dar]]'', a group Fett handpicked to train the Grand [[Army/Legends|Army's]] [[Special forces/Legends|special forces]] [[Clone commando/Legends|clone commandos]],<ref name="GttGAR" /> were responsible for the proliferation of a number of Mandalorian customs among the clones.<ref name="TMPaC" />

Not long after the [[First Battle of Geonosis/Legends|outbreak]] of the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], Mandalorian trainers responsible for educating clone [[Officer/Legends|officers]] on [[Kamino/Legends|Kamino]] were responsible for issuing the traditional battle honor to [[Clone Captain/Legends|Clone Captain]] [[Rex/Legends|Rex]], who chose to display his ''jaig'' on his helmet as well, detailing it in the [[Color/Legends|blue]] coloring of the [[501st Legion/Legends|501st Legion]].<ref name="NewBattlefronts">''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars: New Battlefronts: The Visual Guide]]''</ref> During an off-the-books [[Battle of Onderon/Legends|mission]] to the planet [[Onderon/Legends|Onderon]] that required Rex to forgo his personal [[Trooper/Legends|trooper]] armor, the Republic captain carried his awarded ''jaig'' eyes over to new, non-military attire.<ref name="AWoTF">{{TCW|A War on Two Fronts}}</ref>

Following the harrowing [[Battle of Hypori/Legends|rescue]] of several [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] from the clutches of the [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Separatist]] [[Supreme Commander of the Droid Armies/Legends|Supreme Commander]], [[General/Legends|General]] [[Grievous/Legends|Grievous]], on [[Hypori/Legends|Hypori]], the [[Advanced Recon Commando/Legends|Advanced Recon Commando]] [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Fordo]] was bestowed the right to wear ''jaig'' eyes on his [[Phase II clone trooper armor/Legends|armor]].<ref name="Behind the Armor: A Clones Primer">{{Hyperspace|url=hyperspace/member/insideronline/84/indexp2.html|text=''Behind the Armor: A Clones Primer''|int=Behind the Armor: A Clones Primer}}</ref> During the [[Battle of Coruscant/Legends|Battle of Coruscant]], [[19 BBY/Legends|late]] in the battle, the ARC [[Trooper/Legends|trooper's]] red ''jaig'' eyes could be seen atop his helmet.<ref name="Clone Wars Chapter 23">{{CW|23}}</ref>

The [[Special ops clone trooper/Legends|clone stealth trooper]] [[Clone Commander/Legends|commander]] known as [[Blackout/Legends|Blackout]] wore yellow ''jaig'' eyes on the front of his otherwise black helmet.<ref name="Cat and Mouse">{{TCW|Cat and Mouse}}</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
[[File:Boba_Fett--1st_Preproduction_Prototype_Helmet.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] first production prototype helmet with ''jaig'' eyes]]
''Jaig'' eyes originated in production concept art and early paint explorations by [[Joe Johnston]], for the armor that would be worn by [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] in the second ''[[Star Wars]]'' film, [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''The Empire Strikes Back'']]. Many of Johnston's initial decal designs were abandoned prior to filming, though they would later resurface as sigils adorning the armor of other Mandalorian soldiers, and upon personalized suits of clone trooper armor.

The [[in-universe]] history and cultural significance of ''jaig'' eyes, as well as their full name of ''jai'galaar'la sur'haii'se'', were detailed in the ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'' articles "[[Guide to the Grand Army of the Republic]]" and "[[The Mandalorians: People and Culture]]," written by authors [[Ryan Kaufman (real person)|Ryan Kaufman]] and [[Karen Traviss]].

